    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Late-medieval daggers in widespread use by the mid-1300s. These were long, slim needle-pointed blades with cylindrical grips, usually placed between disc-shaped pommels and crossguards, both called rondels. The blade could either be flat, with one or two sharp edges, diamond-shaped, or triangular.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
